.SH "Detailed Description"
.PP 
An s-expression is represented as a linked structure of elements, where each element is either an \fIatom\fP or \fIlist\fP\&. An atom corresponds to a string, while a list corresponds to an s-expression\&. The following grammar represents our definition of an s-expression:

.PP
.PP
.nf

sexpr  ::= ( sx )
sx     ::= atom sxtail | sexpr sxtail | 'sexpr sxtail | 'atom sxtail | NULL
sxtail ::= sx | NULL
atom   ::= quoted | value
quoted ::= "ws_string"
value  ::= nws_string
.fi
.PP
 

.PP
An atom can either be a quoted string, which is a string containing whitespace (possibly) surrounded by double quotes, or a non-whitespace string that does not require surrounding quotes\&. An element representing an atom will have a type of \fIvalue\fP and data stored in the \fIval\fP field\&. An element of type \fIlist\fP represents an s-expression corresponding to \fIsexpr\fP in the grammar, and will have a pointer to the head of the appropriate s-expression\&. Details regarding these fields and their values given with the fields themselves\&. Notice that a single quote can appear directly before an s-expression or atom, similar to the use in LISP\&. 
.SH "Field Documentation"
.PP 
.SS "\fBatom_t\fP aty"
For elements that represent \fIvalues\fP, this field will specify the specific type of value that it represents\&. This can be used by functions to determine how this value should be printed (ie: how it should be quoted) or interpreted (ie: interpreting s-expressions that are prefixed with a tick-mark\&.)\&. This value also indicates whether or not the programmer should look in the val field or bindata field for the atom data\&. 
.SS "char* bindata"
For elements that represent \fIbinary\fP blobs, this field will point to a memory location where the data resides\&. The length of this memory blob is the next field\&. char* implies byte sized elements\&. This is only used in INLINE_BINARY parser mode\&. \fBIMPORTANT NOTE\fP: The data in this field is freed on a \fBdestroy_sexp()\fP call, so users should copy it to memory they allocate if they wish it to persist after the \fBsexp_t\fP has been freed\&. 
.SS "size_t binlength"
The length of the data pointed at by bindata in bytes\&. 
.SS "struct \fBelt\fP* list"
If the type of the element is \fBSEXP_LIST\fP, this field will contain a pointer to the head element of the list\&. 
.SS "struct \fBelt\fP* next"
The \fInext\fP field is a pointer to the next element in the current expression\&. If this element is the last element in the s-expression, this field will be \fINULL\fP\&. 
.SS "\fBelt_t\fP ty"
The element has a type that determines how the structure is used\&. If the type is \fBSEXP_VALUE\fP, then a programmer knows that either the val field or bindata field is meaningful depending on the value of the aty field, and contains the data associated with this element of the s-expression\&. If the type is \fBSEXP_LIST\fP, then the list field contains a pointer to the s-expression element representing the head of the list\&. For each case, the field for the opposite case contains no meaningful data and using them in any way is likely to cause an error\&. 
.SS "char* val"
If the type of the element is \fBSEXP_VALUE\fP and the aty field is not \fBSEXP_BINARY\fP, this field will contain the actual data represented by this element\&. 
.SS "size_t val_allocated"
Number of bytes allocated for val\&. 
.SS "size_t val_used"
Number of bytes used in val (<= val_allocated)\&. 

